  "prompt": "What does it mean when your left eye twitches?",
  "response": "When your left eye twitches, it's medically known as eyelid myokymia. This involuntary muscle spasm is usually harmless and can be caused by several factors:\n\n1. Common causes:\n- Stress\n- Fatigue\n- Caffeine consumption\n- Lack of sleep\n- Eye strain\n- Alcohol consumption\n- Nutritional imbalances (like low magnesium)\n\n2. Potential triggers:\n- Extended screen time\n- Bright lights\n- Dry eyes\n- Allergies\n- Excessive caffeine or alcohol\n\n3. Usually temporary:\n- Most eye twitches last a few seconds to a few minutes\n- Often resolve on their own\n- Generally not a sign of serious medical condition\n\n4. When to seek medical attention:\n- Twitching persists for weeks\n- Involves entire face\n- Causes eye closure\n- Accompanies other facial symptoms\n- Affects vision\n\n5. Prevention tips:\n- Get adequate sleep\n- Reduce stress\n- Limit caffeine\n- Stay hydrated\n- Practice eye relaxation techniques\n- Take breaks from screens\n\nIf eye twitching becomes persistent or concerning, consult a healthcare professional for proper evaluation.",
